The Downside of Bigness

Shana Randhava, Lauder=E2=80=99s global head of venture investments and inc=
ubation, is credited with orchestrating the three-step, multi-year structur=
e that=E2=80=99s typically the province of private equity. I=E2=80=99m surp=
rised we don=E2=80=99t see more =E2=80=9Ctry before you buy=E2=80=9D-type d=
eals in beauty, but I hope Lauder keeps letting Randhava do her thing. Amon=
g other advantages, the deal structure allowed Deciem to retain much of its=
 indie culture, due in part to its physical distance from the GM Building. =
To this day, The Ordinary remains the only brand in the entire company that=
 doesn=E2=80=99t adhere to ELC=E2=80=99s outdated, prestige-or-bust pricing=
 rules.

Beyond differing viewpoints on price, Kilner and Truaxe=E2=80=99s vision ca=
talyzed the idea that drugstore-priced skincare could also look expensive. =
This, of course, represented a radical shift in consumer
behavior within the industry=E2=80=94especially for Lauder, which finally g=
ave in and started selling on Amazon this year. And even though The Ordinar=
y has managed to buck many of the issues plaguing its parentco=E2=80=99s ot=
her entities, it isn=E2=80=99t immune to market headwinds. Over the past se=
veral months, sales have softened. The skincare line was below plan for the=
 quarter ending September 30, according to Circana data I viewed. (A person=
 familiar with the matter said business is still up year over year and that=
 Deciem will likely surpass $700 million in revenue in fiscal 2025.)

This mirrors much of what=E2=80=99s going on in the rest of the industry, e=
ven at companies faring better than Lauder. In October, L=E2=80=99Or=C3=A9a=
l=E2=80=99s dermatological division=E2=80=94including The Ordinary=E2=80=99=
s direct competitor, CeraVe=E2=80=94widely missed its 11 percent growth est=
imate. (The category increased by just 0.8 percent.) =E2=80=9CThe most sign=
ificant factor impacting their sales is the market,=E2=80=9D said the perso=
n
familiar with the matter. =E2=80=9CSkincare just isn=E2=80=99t as hot as it=
 was.=E2=80=9D

Circana=E2=80=99s data also demonstrates that skincare was the =E2=80=9Csof=
test-growing=E2=80=9D sector of beauty in the third quarter at department a=
nd specialty retail stores=E2=80=93=E2=80=93including Sephora and Ulta Beau=
ty, where The Ordinary is sold. Sun and body care are currently driving gro=
wth in skincare, outpacing the rest of the category, but neither is a core =
competency for The Ordinary. (This could change if Deciem=E2=80=99s newest =
brand, Loopha, which recently launched with hand and body wash, resonates w=
ith The Ordinary=E2=80=99s loyal Gen Z customers.)

Even with the support of the ELC mothership, The Ordinary now faces the sam=
e challenges most startups do when scaling outside the embrace of the found=
er. With size comes more processes and the loss of agility=E2=80=94and, fra=
nkly, the loss of the on-the-ground insights that built the business. =E2=
=80=9CThis would be happening regardless of Est=C3=A9e Lauder=E2=80=99s
involvement,=E2=80=9D said an executive at the conglomerate. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s the downside of becoming big.=E2=80=9D

