          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b>Shana Randhava</=
b>, Lauder=E2=80=99s global head of venture investments and incubation, is =
credited with orchestrating the three-step, multi-year structure that=E2=80=
=99s typically the province of private equity. I=E2=80=99m surprised we don=
=E2=80=99t see more =E2=80=9Ctry before you buy=E2=80=9D-type deals in beau=
ty, but I hope Lauder keeps letting Randhava do her thing. Among other adva=
ntages, the deal structure allowed Deciem to retain much of its indie cultu=
re, due in part to its physical distance from the GM Building. To this day,=
 The Ordinary remains the only brand in the entire company that doesn=E2=80=
=99t adhere to ELC=E2=80=99s outdated, prestige-or-bust pricing rules. <br/=
> <br/>Beyond differing viewpoints on price, Kilner and Truaxe=E2=80=99s vi=
sion catalyzed the idea that drugstore-priced skincare could also look <i>e=
xpensive</i>. This, of course, represented a radical shift in consumer
behavior within the industry=E2=80=94especially for Lauder, which finally g=
ave in and started selling on Amazon this year. And even though The Ordinar=
y has managed to buck many of the issues plaguing its parentco=E2=80=99s ot=
her entities, it isn=E2=80=99t immune to market headwinds. Over the past se=
veral months, sales have softened. The skincare line was below plan for the=
 quarter ending September 30, according to Circana data I viewed. (A person=
 familiar with the matter said business is still up year over year and that=
 Deciem will likely surpass $700 million in revenue in fiscal 2025.)<br/> <=
br/>This mirrors much of what=E2=80=99s going on in the rest of the industr=
y, even at companies faring better than Lauder. In October, L=E2=80=99Or=C3=
=A9al=E2=80=99s dermatological division=E2=80=94including The Ordinary=E2=
=80=99s direct competitor, CeraVe=E2=80=94widely missed its 11 percent grow=
th estimate. (The category increased by just 0.8 percent.) =E2=80=9CThe mos=
t significant factor impacting their sales is the market,=E2=80=9D said the=
 person
familiar with the matter. =E2=80=9CSkincare just isn=E2=80=99t as hot as it=
 was.=E2=80=9D<br/> <br/>Circana=E2=80=99s data also demonstrates that skin=
care was the =E2=80=9Csoftest-growing=E2=80=9D sector of beauty in the thir=
d quarter at department and specialty retail stores=E2=80=93=E2=80=93includ=
ing Sephora and Ulta Beauty, where The Ordinary is sold. Sun and body care =
are currently driving growth in skincare, outpacing the rest of the categor=
y, but neither is a core competency for The Ordinary. (This could change if=
 Deciem=E2=80=99s newest brand, Loopha, which recently launched with hand a=
nd body wash, resonates with The Ordinary=E2=80=99s loyal Gen Z customers.)=
<br/> <br/>Even with the support of the ELC mothership, The Ordinary now fa=
ces the same challenges most startups do when scaling outside the embrace o=
f the founder. With size comes more <i>processes </i>and the loss of agilit=
y=E2=80=94and, frankly, the loss of the on-the-ground insights that built t=
he business. =E2=80=9CThis would be happening regardless of Est=C3=A9e Laud=
er=E2=80=99s
involvement,=E2=80=9D said an executive at the conglomerate. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s the downside of becoming big.=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
         </tr>
